event.solution:
1) Use "-mcmodel=medium" flag when compiling the program. (For GCC, this is the default for recent versions)

2) Limit the scope of visibility for the symbol.

Symbols declared implicitly or explicitly as "extern" can have different scope of visibility:

 - within the compilation unit.

 - within the linked object.

 - globally (this is the default).


There are performance advantages to limiting the scope of visibility. This can be effected by:

- if the symbol is only used within the compilation unit, declare it as "static".

Example:

	static void foo(void);

	static int voo;


- if the symbol is only needed within the linked object, use the GNU extention "__attribute((visibility("hidden")))".

Example:

	void foo(void) __attribute__((visibility("hidden")));

	int voo __attribute__((nocommon,visibility("hidden")));


- if there is need for the symbol to be referenced externally to the linked object, there is a technique which can be more performant at the expense of not being able to override the use of the symbol within that object. Declare the symbol as hidden and use the symbol within the object normally. Declare an alias of the symbol which is externally visible.

Example:

	int __voo __attribute__((nocommon,visibility("hidden")));

	int voo __attribute__((alias("__foo")));


	void __foo(void) __attribute__((visibility("hidden")));

	extern void foo(void) __attribute__((alias("__foo")));

1) Remove unnecessary "volatile" from variables.

2) Use local variables instead of pointer references.

Pseudo-example:

 loop {

	*p = foo(*p);

 }


 - Change to:

 p = *p

 loop {

	p = foo(p);

 }

 *p = p;
